 book discovers her life through the communities of girls and women around her: the free and enslaved women who raised her in Wells, Maine; the Wabanaki women who cared for her, catechized her, and taught her to work as an Indian girl; the French-Canadian and Native girls who were her classmates in the Ursuline school; and the Ursuline nuns who led her to a religious life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNunszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 0aNunszQuébec (Province)vBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106677140 cprintz978030021821340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030022462740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300224627/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY